An "Initial Development Entrepreneur" (IDE) is the individual who first envisions a product or service for sale. They usually have a deep familiarity with the market and the sector in which they operate, allowing them to see gaps in the market that may be filled by innovative new goods and services. A small or medium-sized enterprise (SME) is a company that is not as huge as a multinational corporation but is nonetheless very sizable. In order to survive, these companies often focus on specific niches and are nimble enough to respond rapidly to market shifts. The IDE introduces novel concepts to the market, whereas the SME fuels technological advancement and business expansion within a certain sector. 